<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-10-05T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-10-05T14:00:00-05:00" n="894" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d894">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">300.115(39) Korsholm/5: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Chargé in Germany</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-05T14:00:00-05:00">October 5,
                                    1939—2 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>639. Department is advised that Swedish M/S <hi rend="italic">Korsholm</hi>, also Estonian SS <hi rend="italic">Minna</hi> and
                            Norwegian SS <hi rend="italic">Brott</hi>,<note n="92" xml:id="d894fn92">By telegram No. 1658, October 10, 5 p.m., the Chargé in Germany
                                reported that the steamship <hi rend="italic">Brott</hi> and cargo
                                had been released (300.115(39)Korsholm/9).</note> each with a cargo
                            of wood pulp or wood pulp products, consigned to various concerns in the
                            United States, have been detained at Swinemünde, Kiel, and Sivinemünde,
                            respectively.</p>
                        <p>In the general interest of American commerce, ascertain the reasons for
                            such detentions and what action German authorities contemplate taking
                            with reference to the cargoes.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>